Why this exists
The portal is meant to feel like a single “front door” for people who work with AI tooling, research tooling, and take action through agents and orchestrators that can reason over what they find and trigger automations across Jenkins, Bitbucket, Jira, Confluence, and more.. Phase 1 is about making it usable inside the company: people should be able to enter using company identity, the system should know who they are, and the portal should guide them toward what they need — whether that’s connecting a research tool like IDA, discovering available agents and MCP servers, or deploying their own agent safely.

This page describes Phase 1 in a way that focuses on user experience, system flow, and what value it gives — not a deep technical guide.



What Phase 1 will feel like
A user opens the portal and sees two login paths. Local/system users (like admin) can still log in with credentials. Most users will use a new button: “Login with Company Credentials.” Clicking it redirects to Authentik, the user signs in, and returns to the portal already recognized.

From that moment, the portal behaves like it knows the user: it greets them by name, shows only the tabs they are allowed to access, and captures usage and activity so admins can understand adoption, usage patterns, and ownership. Under the hood, Phase 1 makes the database the source of truth for identity, permissions, registrations, marketplace entries, deployments, and usage metrics — and it establishes a consistent ownership rule: users can manage/delete what they own; admins can manage/delete everything.



Company login (SSO) and how the portal session works
When we choose Company Login, Authentik authenticates us and returns a signed identity token that contains user properties (email, full name, groups, and other claims). The portal validates that token and then does two important things.

First, it records the login and identity attributes in the database. This supports the admin view in Analytics: who logged in, when, how many times, and later, how portal activity correlates with usage and adoption.

Second, the portal issues a portal-specific session token for the frontend (this matches what already exists in the code today): after the Authentik login succeeds, we still use the portal token (Authorization: Bearer <portal-token>) for all API calls. The token has an expiration controlled by configuration, and the token details are persisted so the system can manage session lifecycle cleanly.

If this is the user’s first time, the portal automatically creates them in the users table using what came from Authentik (including group membership). If the user already exists, the portal refreshes identity fields and continues the login statistics and activity logging.

The only configuration needed here is the Authentik OIDC connection (issuer/address plus client id/secret and redirect URL) and the portal’s own JWT signing and expiration settings — kept in .env so the portal can be deployed to different environments without code changes.

