Authorization and tab visibility (admin-managed users + groups)
Phase 1 makes permissions explicit and manageable, not implicit and scattered.

The portal will maintain users and groups in the database. Users are created/updated from Authentik on login. Groups are also derived from Authentik and stored so we can use them consistently for authorization. On top of those tables, Phase 1 adds a clear admin-only authorization experience: an admin can decide which portal areas (tabs/sections) are visible and which actions are allowed for both users and groups.

In practice, this appears as an admin panel that includes a permissions matrix. The admin can assign access for features like Research, Marketplace, DevOps/Investigations, Analytics, BI, and Settings. The same underlying policy is enforced twice: the frontend uses it to render the sidebar and hide tabs that are not permitted, and the backend uses it to block API calls that should not be allowed (even if someone tries to call them directly).

This makes the portal feel clean: users never see tabs they can’t use, and admins get a real control surface to govern the platform as adoption grows.



